Mission:
EXEC-001

Title:
Execution Engine

Goal:
Close the loop from "Atlas generated an engineering package" to "there is real code" — the missing link toward Atlas autonomously building a new app on command.

Focus:
ExecutionEngine module (scripts/atlas/executionEngine.ts) and mission.implement AI task
Claude drafts a small, focused code proposal from a mission's real architecture brief and validation plan
Real repository context gathering: scans mission text for file paths and reads them from disk (up to 20k chars each) so Claude grounds proposals in real code instead of guessing
Proposed files are written to a review-only proposed-changes/ folder — never the working tree directly
A machine-readable proposal-manifest.json alongside CHANGES.md so the Apply Engine knows exactly what to apply
Path safety allowlist/denylist so proposals can never touch package.json, .env, node_modules, or escape the repo
Manual CLI trigger (npm run atlas:execute, entrypoint scripts/atlas-execute.ts) so a human always decides when code gets drafted
Apply Engine (scripts/atlas/applyEngine.ts) writes a reviewed proposal into the real working tree and archives proposed-changes/ to applied-<timestamp>/
Manual apply CLI (npm run atlas:apply, entrypoint scripts/atlas-apply.ts) and an automatic local-only apply-bridge (127.0.0.1:8791/apply, started by atlas-runtime.ts) that Atlas Control's CEO Inbox "Approve" button calls for package-review items
ensureExecutionProposal (scripts/atlas-runtime.ts) automatically drafts a code proposal for the runtime's current top-priority mission once it has a real engineering package — no manual npm run atlas:execute required — with a failure-backoff marker (engineering/packages/<ID>/execution-attempt.json) so a persistent problem never spams the Claude API every cycle
CEO Inbox now distinguishes "package ready to review" from "code proposal ready to review" (buildCandidateApprovals in scripts/atlas/realCompanyData.ts) so the CEO only ever needs to see a notification and click Approve — never a CLI step, for either drafting or applying
Test execution and git automation — see EXEC-002: automatic post-apply typecheck + commit-message drafting + staging, while the actual `git commit` still always requires a human

Constraints:
No automatic writes to the working tree, ever, without an explicit CEO approval click (or explicit `npm run atlas:apply` CLI command) — never from the background decision loop on its own
Drafting a code proposal (writing only to the review-only proposed-changes/ folder, never the working tree) may now happen automatically from the background loop — reviewing and applying it never does
No mock code generation — requires a real ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, fails honestly otherwise
Every proposed file path validated against an allowlist before it touches disk, and re-validated independently again before being applied
The apply-bridge server binds to 127.0.0.1 only — never reachable from outside the local machine
Provider-independent through the existing AI Orchestrator — no Claude-specific coupling in the engine itself

Success:
Once Atlas picks a mission as its top priority, the runtime automatically generates its engineering package and then its code proposal — no CLI required. The CEO only ever sees a CEO Inbox notification ("Review code proposal · <MISSION-ID>") and clicks Approve, which writes the reviewed files into the real working tree and archives the proposal, ready for git diff review. `npm run atlas:execute` / `npm run atlas:apply` remain available as manual fallbacks for testing or if the runtime isn't running.
